column168: WHILE BEING UNLOADED FROM A LOCKHEED ELECTRA CARGO AIRCRAFT, ONE PACKAGE OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL(I-131) WAS DROPPED FROM A HEIGHT OF APPROXIMATELY 9 F EET ONTO THE ASPHALT RAMP.  THE AREA WAS WET WITH STANDING WATER AT THE TIM E AND THE BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE BECAME SOAKED.  THE PACKAGE ALSO HAD A SMAL L TEAR IN THE FIBREBOARD OUTER CARTON.  DUE TO THE RADIOACTIVE ELEMENT BEIN G IN LIQUID FORM AND THE SOAKED CARTON, IT WAS NOT POSSIBLE TO DETERMINE AN Y LEAKAGE BY A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, ALL PERSONNEL WHICH CAME IN CONTACT WERE ADVISED TO STAND BY FOR A CHECK O F POSSIBLE RADIOACTIVE CONTAMINATION, AND THE PROPER AUTHORIZES WERE NOTIFI ED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE TO CHECK FOR RADIOACTIVE CONTAMINATION. ASSISTANCE WAS RECEIVED FROM THE MICHIGAN STATE POLICE AND A TECHNICIAN FRO M THE MICHIGAN STATE DIVISION OF RADIOLOGICAL HEATH RESPONDED WITH TESTING EQUIPMENT AND CONFIRMED THAT THERE WAS NO RADIATION LEAKAGE FROM THE PACKAG E AND THAT THE INNER CONTAINER WAS UNDAMAGED AND INTACT.  BASED ON THIS INF ORMATION, AFFECTED PERSONNEL WERE RELEASED AND THE OUTER CONTAINER WAS REPA IRED AND THE PACKAGE RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.
